        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:51:"An Interview with VITANI Bottled Cocktails Founders";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:98:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/2015/12/an-interview-with-vitani-bottled-cocktails-founders/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:107:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/2015/12/an-interview-with-vitani-bottled-cocktails-founders/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 04 Dec 2015 16:50:01 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/?p=1159";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4871:"If you’re a cocktail lover (which you should be) and you’ve been to any of the trendier lounges in Chicago lately, you’ve probably noticed them offering up house-bottled cocktails. They’re a unique way to serve drinks and they offer the added benefit of immediate gratification – no more waiting for your bartender to pour and stir his way to perfection. Tired of the wait and looking to enjoy their favorite cocktails at the drop of hat, Chicago natives Eric and Jackie Gichner decided to tackle bringing bottled cocktails to your local grocery. <a href="http://www.drinkvitani.com/" target="_blank">VITANI</a>, is the result.

<b>When and what was the "Aha" moment like when you two decided to start VITANI? Where did the name come from? </b>

<i>One night, we were at a restaurant with friends drinking dirty martinis. We love to drink these when we’re out, but suddenly wondered why we didn’t make them more at home. Making them at home can be messy, and they rarely turn out as well as when a bartender makes them. Right then, the idea was born and we decided to create a bottled martini that replicated the bartender experience at home (or wherever you decide to drink VITANI!).</i>

<i>VITANI has been in the works for over three years and launched this past May, and the entire process has been extremely rewarding. The name comes from two letters from each of our three children’s names—the VI in David, the TA in Taylor, and the NI in Dani. </i>

<b>What has the Chicago market's response been to the product so far?</b>

<i>We feel so fortunate to have aligned ourselves with the right people, especially our distributor, who has worked tirelessly to make VITANI available in as many stores as possible. We are in nearly 100 stores around Chicagoland! When people taste VITANI, they are surprised that it really is like a true martini—one that a bartender would make! The challenge with a new product like this is getting it into stores so people can try it; once they do, they become repeat customers.</i>

<b>That's great to hear. Will we be seeing VITANI in bars in the near future or is a retail setting the main focus at the moment?</b>

<i>Retail is the main focus since VITANI is "taking the place of a bartender". That being said, VITANI would be perfect for bars where they would be in a tub (similar to a beer tub) to be dispersed quickly or where a bartender may want to pour a quick easy drink instead of creating their own. </i>

<b>Was aluminum a decision made to set yourselves apart versus competitors or was sustainability top of mind when discussing packaging? Perhaps both? </b>

<i>It’s definitely both. While we certainly wanted to set ourselves apart from other brands on the market, the bottle is both sustainable and extremely portable—which is important when you’re making a bottled cocktail. The bottles also chill quickly due to the aluminum, so that makes it easy to chill and enjoy right away.</i>

<b>It sounds like the inspiration for the Dirty Martini was Jackie's love for them, but where did the inspiration for the Innovation Series flavors come from? Any new flavors in the works you're willing to discuss?</b>

<i>For the Innovation Series, we knew we wanted to go with what’s on-trend, and those flavors aligned with trends of the moment. Our next phase is launching the larger, 750ml bottles, which will be in stores in early 2016. We hope to work on new flavors and concepts towards the end of 2016, but nothing in the works just yet!</i>

<b>750ml bottles take you from single-servings to more a group-oriented drink. Do you see VITANI taking the place of wine in social settings?</b>

<i>There are wine drinkers and there are martini drinkers (some may be both). This may not be taking the place of wine but this gives the option for those who prefer a martini. </i>

<b>In that same vein, where do you see VITANI 1 to 5 years from now? What's your dream for the brand?</b>

<i>We would love to see VITANI throughout the Midwest in the next year and as a nationally recognized brand with additional product offerings in the next 5.</i>

If you ask me, Eric, Jackie and the VITANI brand are well on their way to achieving that first anniversary goal. Having just launched in May of 2015, they’ve exploded onto the Chicago scene. You can find out more about their entire lineup of martinis <a href="http://www.drinkvitani.com/our-martinis/" target="_blank">here</a>.

Cheers!

