        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39:"Local Cideries for National Cider Month";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:86:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/2015/10/local-cideries-for-national-cider-month/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:95:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/2015/10/local-cideries-for-national-cider-month/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Oct 2015 20:40:39 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:45:"http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/?p=1154";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3550:"If you live in the Midwest, you know that apple orchards and fall go hand in hand. In fact, they pair so well that October has been christened “National Cider Month” specifically to highlight the beautiful booze produced from using those orchard-fresh apples.

For some, mass-produced ciders like <a href="http://www.smithandforgehardcider.com/" target="_blank">Smith &amp; Forge</a> (a MillerCoors product), <a href="http://www.jappleseed.com/" target="_blank">Johnny Appleseed</a> (an AB-InBev product) and <a href="angryorchard.com" target="_blank">Angry Orchard</a> (a Boston Beer Company product) will cut it. For others, the cider needs to be as fresh and local as the apples they hand-pick at the orchard around the corner. While there is nothing wrong with gulping down mass-produced products, you have to admit that being a part of the second group just sounds better. Local apples used by a local cidery to produce a locally consumed cider is about as American as it gets after all.

With that being said, I would like to highlight some local and regional cideries that are definitely worth your time. While this is by no means a definitive list of Chicagoland or Midwest cideries, this should definitely be enough to get you started.

Cheers!

<a href="http://www.appleknockerhardcider.com/Home_Page.html" target="_blank"><b>Apple Knocker</b></a> – Cobden, IL

These guys are right here in Illinois and can their products. On top of that, their cidermaster has a winemaking background, so that’s definitely worth noting.

<a href="http://www.primacider.com/" target="_blank"><b>Prima Cider</b></a> – Long Grove, IL

Another local producer. They’ve been making cider for 35 years and they source their apples from WI, IL and MI. On top of that, they’ve got an underground cellar and small orchard on-site for experimentation.

<a href="http://www.bnektar.com/" target="_blank"><b>B. Nektar</b></a> – Ferndale, MI

They started off making mead (aka honey wine), and have since made a name for themselves in the cider world. They produce some really left of center ciders using ingredients most traditional cideries don’t even think about touching.

<a href="http://organicscrumpy.com/" target="_blank"><b>J.K.’s Farmhouse Ciders</b></a> – Flushing, MI

I had to include J.K.’s because their cider was the first hard cider I tried that really blew me away. They consistently produce a stellar product that really sets a benchmark for hard cider to live up to in my mind.

<a href="http://www.sietsemaorchards.com/" target="_blank"><b>Sietsema’s</b></a> – Ada, MI

Sietsema’s produced one of the first dry-hopped ciders I had the chance of trying for Cider Summit here in Chicago a couple of years ago. Thought leadership like that ensures they’ll be around for quite some time.

<a href="http://vandermill.com/" target="_blank"><b>Vander Mill</b></a> – Spring Lake, MI

If you haven’t seen Vandermill on tap and in 16 oz. cans here in Chicago you’ve been living under a rock. They’re coming up on their 10 year anniversary, but they’ve really taken the Midwest by storm over the past few years.

