Though Trumer Pils was originally brewed in Austria, they've been brewing it in Berkeley, CA since 2004, making it another fantastic American bottle of suds. And when I say fantastic, I mean it. This German Pilsner is rocking an <a href="http://www.beeradvocate.com/beer/profile/11017/12679/?ba=bros" target="_blank">86 on BeerAdvocate</a> right now, and rightfully so! I rarely share my opinion on brews, but I have to say that this is one of the best German Pilsners being brewed in the U.S. right now. It is remarkably refreshing and clean, not to mention true to style, making it the perfect summer beer.

Instead of picking up a sixer of "one of the other guys," I highly encourage you to go out of your way to try Trumer Pils. I promise, you won't be disappointed. This beer might come in the classic green bottle you've come to expect from a German Pilsner, but it is head and shoulders above the look-alikes, guaranteed.

Cheers!

P.S. If you really need convincing, or have a friend that "doesn't like beer," here's a fantastic summer cocktail you can make using Trumer Pils as well. This was made popular by the <a href="http://redroosterharlem.com/" target="_blank">Red Rooster Harlem</a> in NYC, but sadly, it no longer graces their menu.

El Matador
<ul>
	<li>2 oz. Herradura Blanco tequila</li>
	<li>1 oz. fresh lime juice</li>
	<li>0.5 oz. agave nectar</li>
	<li>2 medium strawberries and 4 basil leafs</li>
</ul>
Muddle the strawberries and basil before adding the liquid ingredients. Strain over ice into a rocks glass before topping off with Trumer Pils. Garnish the rim with chili pepper and salt if you wish and add a whole strawberry and basil leaf for looks.

