<a href="http://www.thatcherscider.co.uk/product/the-cider/premium/thatchers-green-goblin-cider.ashx" target="_blank">Green Goblin</a> is a medium-bodied cider, made with bittersweet apples, that starts off slightly sweet and finishes slightly dry. It's the quintessential English cider, entering the U.S. market at a time where virtually every other mass-produced cider is overly sweet. To say that it's refreshing and drinkable would be an understatement. Those of you who were dismayed when <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/hoppy-times/2014/04/strongbow-discontinues-their-original-recipe/" target="_blank">Strongbow discontinued their original recipe</a> here in the U.S. before introducing something much sweeter, should definitely give Thatchers Green Goblin a try. I think you'll be pleasantly surprised with what I consider a great go-to cider.

If you're not one to drink things straight, my recommendation here is to go with the classic Cider Jack. It's an incredibly easy cocktail to throw together and an incredibly easy cocktail to drink. Pour 2 oz. of Laird's Applejack over ice and mix in roughly 6 oz. of Thatchers Green Goblin to taste. It's as easy as that. The best places to get your hands on a bottle here in Chicago is <a href="http://www.binnys.com/beer/Thatchers_Green_Goblin_Oak_Aged_Cider_54147.html" target="_blank">here</a> at Binny's. I suggest you pick up a few and let me know what you think.

Cheers!

