<b>I would assume you're a home brewer as well, but you know what they say about assumptions. So, have you dabbled in brewing at home?</b>

You’d assume correctly. I’ve been an avid homebrewer since 2008. My wife is really the one that lit the fire when she gifted me a <a href="http://us.diybeer.com/">Cooper’s DIY Beer Kit</a> for Christmas that year and I’ve been hooked ever since. Like most homebrewers, I started brewing with extract kits but I quickly moved into all-grain by the end of my first year. I typically brew about once a month. I go through phases when it comes to which styles I like to brew, but right now I’m experimenting with the saison-style and other wild and funky beers.

<b>My assumption is that you've probably had the chance to meet some industry greats making beer and beard-centric products. Any experiences stick out to you?</b>

As a homebrewer and craft beer writer (my blog is <a href="http://artfulpint.com/">The Artful Pint</a>) I’ve had the opportunity to interact with many of the industry’s most well-known personalities. I’m not one to name-drop and I’ve never been a hero worshipper, but I respect the contributions of all of the members of the craft beer community. I’ve never met a kinder, more open-minded and welcoming group of people as those behind craft beer. As for the beard community, I’m still a relative newcomer so knowing and being known are both works in progress.

<b>How about the state of the craft beer industry in general. What’s your opinion about where we’re at and where the beer scene is headed?</b>

What started out as a niche movement barely making a dent in the overall beer market is quickly turning into a serious threat to the large brewing conglomerates of the world. Sales of beer overall are flat to declining while sales of craft beer continue to surge. According to the <a href="https://www.brewersassociation.org/statistics/national-beer-sales-production-data/">Brewer’s Association’s last report</a>, in 2014 craft beer accounted for 11% of the total volume of beer sold in the US. This is double what it was just four short years ago. To put this into perspective, in 2005 there were 1447 licensed breweries in the US. By 2014 there were nearly 3500. Over the last two years alone, craft beer has experienced nearly 20% growth.

While I don’t think that this type of hockey stick growth is sustainable in the long-term, I do believe that we are still far from reaching a national craft beer market saturation point. Consumers of craft beer have an unshakable thirst and craft breweries continue to open in record numbers in an attempt to sate it. Craft beer continues to create trends and further define their industry every year. It’s a really exciting time to be a beer drinker and beer writer. It’s pretty hard for me to keep up with everything that’s going on.

If I had to make a few predictions about the craft beer market I’d say that the age of the IPA as the king of styles is reaching its end, session beers are here to stay along with a general downward trend in overall beer ABV% and that we’ll start to see more and more breweries resurrecting once-dead traditional styles like lambic, gratzer and gueze.

<b>How do you see beer-related products fitting into that?</b>

Where there’s smoke there’s fire and this axiom as it applies to craft beer-related products definitely holds true. For any market that’s experiencing a boom like we’re seeing in craft beer there are sure to be the ancillary markets that inevitably crop up around them. If there’s a way to make money by riding the coattails of craft beer, chances are there’s an entrepreneur that’s trying to take advantage of it, including yours truly. Apparel, growlers, glassware, food, consultancies, art, and, my personal bailiwick, personal care. If you find a way to tie your product to craft beer you can tap into a rabid and highly loyal market that craves anything craft beer.

There’s clearly money to be made in the craft beer products market and the sheer volume of independent businesses and larger wholesalers we’re seeing are a testament to that. Whether one is successful is as much of a crapshoot as anything else. As a small business that manufacturers beardcare products, I see how intense the competition even within my small market can be. There are hundreds of small businesses making beard balms and beard oils and they are all going after anyone with a beard. I knew I needed to differentiate but I also knew that this focus would potentially alienate a much larger customer base. By offering only hop-centric products I’ve made my job even more challenging. I go after the craft beer loving bearded directly, but if I can attract some non-craft beer drinking bearded and get them to cross over, I’ve done double duty.

<b>I'm sure that beard has taken a bit of time to refine. Was caring for your own beard the inspiration for The Beerded Beard Company?</b>

I view my beard like a bonsai tree and like a bonsai it must be nurtured, refined, molded and shaped. One has to be careful, though, too much fussing can lead to a beard unable to live up to its potential. I’ve got a long way to go, but I think my beard is off to a good start. It also helps that my wife encourages me to continue the bearded lifestyle. She’s a huge fan of it.

Beards are definitely experiencing a resurgence in popularity. I’ve had facial hair in some form or another ever since I could grow it, but didn’t really start growing a full beard until I was in my late twenties. My current beard is the result of about 18 months of continuous growth and since I don’t have what you’d consider a traditional job I’ve been able to go a bit crazy with it. As it grew longer and fuller and I began to pay more attention to its maintenance and care, I started to dabble with beardcare products including oils, balms and waxes. There are a lot of them out there.

The market for beardcare products is exploding with what seems like dozens of little manufacturers all over the world entering the market every day. I never really cared for most of the products that were on the market mostly because I didn’t like the scents they were using – sandalwood, patchouli, cedar, musk, jasmine – they made my beard smell like my dad’s closet. It was only a matter of time before I started to make my own and it just made sense for me to combine my love of craft beer and hops with my desire for a beardcare product I really enjoyed. After several months of trial and error the Beerded Beard Company was born.

<b>Where do you source the ingredients for your products? Any plans to expand the line-up?</b>

I make an effort to source many of my ingredients from local and regional suppliers. The key ingredient to The Beerded Beard Company’s product line, hops, are currently grown by the grower-owners of <a href="https://www.hopunion.com/">Hop Union LLC</a> of Yakima, Washington. I use the same hops that I brew with so I’ve found the most knowledgeable and reliable sources for my hops to be my local and regional homebrewing supply shops. They’re typically up on the latest and greatest in the world of hops and they’re normally able to secure some of the most popular varieties like Citra (often in short supply) making it easier for me to focus on making great products instead of wondering about my supply chain.

As for expanding the line-up, I recently launched the new <a href="http://beerdedbeard.com/shop/beard-care/leshers-hopstache-100-all-natural-hop-infused-mustache-wax/">HopStache Mustache Wax</a> in both Citra and Cascade. This was the 4<sup>th</sup> product and the third in the beardcare line. I also have the HopSmacker lip balm and a limited edition I did using Australian Galaxy and Topaz hops. I don’t have any immediate plans for anything new but I’m always tinkering in the workshop. If anything I may trim the number of hop varieties I currently offer (which is now 7) and/or add a new hop variety to the mix. I developed a very unique method for extracting the essential oils and fragrance from raw hops that really gives me tremendous flexibility when it comes to which hops I can use in my products.

<b>Anything else you want everyone to know about The Beerded Beard Company?</b>

Founded in July 2014. I am currently the only employee. All products are made in my home workshop in Cleveland. I’ve sold products to customers in 12 different countries. I currently offer my products in seven different hop varieties. The only fragrance found in Beerded Beard Company products is that which is imparted by the hop essential oils used in the formulations. I manufacture my own hop essence using a multi-step extraction and purification process I developed over the course of several years.

If you want to purchase any of The Beerded Beard Company’s products or get in touch with Bob <a href="http://beerdedbeard.com/">click here</a>.

Cheers!

